window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2024>1>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2024","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"FLUID AT REST : EQUILIBRIUM OF BODIES: ARCHIMEDES\u2019 PRINCIPLE","question":"You are provided a retort stand, a spring balance, masses, a beaker containing water, another beaker containing a liquid labelled, L, and other necessary apparatus.    (i) Suspend the mass, m = 20 g on the spring balance and measure the weight in air, WA in Newton.    (ii) Immerse the suspended mass completely in water and measure the weight in water, WW in Newton. Evaluate U1 = WA - WW.    (iii) Immerse the suspended mass completely in the liquid L of the same volume with water and measure the weight in liquid WL. Evaluate U2 = WA - WL    (iv) Repeat the procedure for m = 40 g, 60 g, 80 g, and 100 g respectively. In each case, evaluate WA, WW, U1, WL, U2.    (v) Tabulate the readings.    (vi) Plot a graph of U1, on the vertical axis and U2, on the horizontal axis starting both axes from the origin (0,0).     (vii) Determine the slope, s, of the graph.    (viii) Evaluate k = 1s\\frac{1}{s}s1\u200b    (ix) State two precautions taken to ensure accurate results.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"S/Nm(g)WA(N)WW(N)U1(N)WL(N)U2(N)1200.200.160.040.180.022400.400.320.080.360.043600.600.460.140.500.104800.800.680.160.680.1251001.000.800.200.720.16        (vii) s = \u25b3U1\u25b3U2\\frac{\u25b3U_{1}}{\u25b3U_{2}}\u25b3U2\u200b\u25b3U1\u200b\u200b = U12\u2212U11U22\u2212U21\\frac{U1_{2}-U1_{1}}{U2_{2}-U2_{1}}U22\u200b\u2212U21\u200bU12\u200b\u2212U11\u200b\u200b = 0.18\u22120.070.14\u22120.02\\frac{0.18-0.07}{0.14-0.02}0.14\u22120.020.18\u22120.07\u200b = 0.110.12\\frac{0.11}{0.12}0.120.11\u200b = 0.92    (viii) k = 1s\\frac{1}{s}s1\u200b = 10.92\\frac{1}{0.92}0.921\u200b = 1.09    (ix) Precautions:    1. I ensured the spring balance was zeroed before taking readings to account for zero error.    2. I used clean and dry equipment to prevent contamination or alteration of the liquid properties.    3. I suspended the mass securely to avoid fluctuations or errors in readings.    4. I ensured that the mass did not touch the base of the beaker during immersion to prevent inaccurate weight measurements.    5. I avoided parallax errors when reading the spring balance by aligning my eyes perpendicular to the scale.    6. I ensured the mass was fully submerged in both water and liquid L without air bubbles clinging to it to maintain accurate measurements.    7. I handled the equipment gently to avoid disturbing the liquids or creating ripples that could affect the readings.    8. I repeated readings for consistency and recorded results in a tabular format for clarity and verification.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2024>1>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2024","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"FLUID AT REST : EQUILIBRIUM OF BODIES: ARCHIMEDES\u2019 PRINCIPLE","question":"State the Archimede's Principle.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Archimedes' Principle states that when a body is wholly or partially immersed in a fluid, it experiences an upward buoyant force (upthrust) equal in magnitude to the weight of the fluid displaced by the body.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2024>1>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2024","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"FLUID AT REST : VOLUME, DENSITY AND RELATIVE DENSITY","question":"State two differences between density and relative density.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Here are several differences between density and relative density:    1.\tDefinition:  Density is the mass per unit volume of a substance, expressed in kg/m\u00b3 or g/cm\u00b3.  Relative density is the ratio of the density of a substance to the density of a reference substance (usually water for liquids and solids, or air for gases) and has no unit.    2.\tUnits:  Density has specific units (e.g., kg/m\u00b3, g/cm\u00b3).  Relative density is dimensionless and unitless because it is a ratio.    3.\tCalculation:  Density is calculated as Density = MassVolume\\frac{Mass}{Volume}VolumeMass\u200b.  Relative density is calculated as   Relative Density=Density of SubstanceDensity of Reference Substance.  4.\tMeasurement:  Density requires measurement of both mass and volume.  Relative density compares densities and often requires determining buoyancy or displacement.    5.\tContext:  Density gives the actual compactness of matter in a substance.  Relative density provides a comparison of the substance's density with a standard, indicating whether it will sink or float in the reference fluid.    6.\tApplications:  Density is used in calculations for engineering, materials science, and physics.  Relative density is used to determine buoyancy and to identify substances without needing absolute density values.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2024>2>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2024","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"Use the diagram above to carry out the following instructions.    You are provided a rectangular glass prism, optical pins, thumb pins, drawing board, plain sheets of paper and other necessary apparatus.    (i) Fix a plain paper on the drawing board using the thumb pins.     (ii) Place the rectangular glass prism on the paper and trace its outline ABCD.    (iii) Draw a normal  N1 , to meet AB at O such that |AO| is 4 cm.    (iv) Draw an incident ray, MO, such that it makes an angle, \u03b8 = 65\u00b0 with AB.    (v) Place two optical pins P1, and P2, on MO and replace the glass prism on its outline.    (vi) View P1, and P2, from DC and place two other pins P3, and P4 such that they lie in a straight line with P1, and P2. Remove the glass block.    (vii) Draw a line to join P3, and P4 to meet DC at E, Draw another normal  N1  at E and join EO.    (viii) Draw a circle of radius 3 cm with the centre at O and draw lines XY and QR perpendicular to  N1 .    (x) Measure and record the lines XY and QR. Evaluate \u03b3 = (XY + QR).    (x) Repeat the procedure for \u03b8 = 55\u00b0, 45\u00b0, 35\u00b0 and 25\u00b0 respectively. In each case, measure and record r, XY, QR and \u03b3.     (xi) Tabulate your readings.    (xii) Plot a graph of \u03b3 on the vertical axis and QR on the horizontal axis starting both axes from the origin, (0,0).    (xiii) Determine the slope, s, of the graph.    (xiv) Evaluate s-1.    (xv) State two precautions taken to ensure accurate results. [attach your traces to your answer booklet]","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"S/N\u03b8\u00b0r\u00b0XY(cm)QR(cm)\u03b3(cm)165151.10.61.7250201.71.02.7345241.91.23.1435302.51.43.9525352.71.84.5        (xiii) s = \u25b3\u03b3\u25b3QR\\frac{\u25b3\u03b3}{\u25b3QR}\u25b3QR\u25b3\u03b3\u200b = \u03b32\u2212\u03b31QR2\u2212QR1\\frac{\u03b3_{2}-\u03b3_{1}}{QR_{2}-QR_{1}}QR2\u200b\u2212QR1\u200b\u03b32\u200b\u2212\u03b31\u200b\u200b = 4.1\u221221.6\u22120.7\\frac{4.1-2}{1.6-0.7}1.6\u22120.74.1\u22122\u200b = 2.10.9\\frac{2.1}{0.9}0.92.1\u200b = 2.33    (xiv) s-1 = 1s\\frac{1}{s}s1\u200b = 12.33\\frac{1}{2.33}2.331\u200b = 0.43    (xv) Precautions:    1. I ensured that the optical pins were vertically erect for accurate alignment.    2. I avoided parallax error when reading the protractor to measure angles.    3. I fixed the plain sheet of paper firmly on the drawing board to prevent it from shifting during tracing.    4. I maintained even spacing between the optical pins to enhance precision in alignment.    5. I avoided placing excessive pressure on the pins to prevent distortion of the paper or displacement of the prism.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2024>2>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2024","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"State the  first law of refraction","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The first law of refraction, also known as Snell's Law, states:    The incident ray, the refracted ray, and the normal to the interface at the point of incidence all lie in the same plane.    This law ensures the geometric relationship between these rays is consistent during the refraction process.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2024>2>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2024","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"A ray of light travels from air to a denser medium of refractive index of 1.7. If it is refracted at 30\u00b0 to the normal, calculate the angle of incidence.    (Provide your answer to 2 d.p and without the degree sign)","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"n = sin\u2061(i)sin\u2061(r)\\frac{\\sin{\\left(i\\right)}}{\\sin{\\left(r\\right)}}sin(r)sin(i)\u200b    1.7 = sin\u2061(i)sin\u2061(30)\\frac{\\sin{\\left(i\\right)}}{\\sin{\\left(30\\right)}}sin(30)sin(i)\u200b    1.7 = sin\u2061(i)0.5\\frac{\\sin{\\left(i\\right)}}{0.5}0.5sin(i)\u200b    sin i = 0.85    i = sin-1(0.85)    i = 58.21\u00b0","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2024>3>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2024","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : CURRENT ELECTRICITY","question":"You are provided with two resistance wires labelled: A and B, standard resistor Rx = 1 \u03a9, metre bridge, cell of emf, E, key, Rheostat Rh, galvanometer and other apparatus.    Use the circuit diagram as a guide to perform the experiment.    (i) Connect Rx in the left hand gap of the metre bridge, a length L = 100 cm of wire, in the right hand gap and the other apparatus as shown.    (ii) Determine and record the balance point, P, on the metre bridge wire NQ,    (iii) Measure and record Lx = NP and Ly = PQ.    (iv) Evaluate R1 = (LyLx\\frac{L_{y}}{L_{x}}Lx\u200bLy\u200b\u200b)Rx.    (v) Repeat the procedure for four other values of L = 90 cm, 80 cm, 70 cm and 60 cm. In each case, determine and record the balance point P, and evaluate R1.    (vi) Repeat the experiment with the second wire B, Obtain the balance point P and evaluate R2 in each case.    (vii) Tabulate the readings.    (viii) Plot a graph of R2 on the vertical axis and R1, on the horizontal axis.    (ix) Determine the slope, s, of the graph.    (x) Evaluate k = &radic;s&nbsp;    (xi) State two precautions taken to ensure accurate results.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"S/NL(cm)Lx(cm)Ly(cm)R1\u03a9Lx(cm)Ly(cm)R2\u03a91100.015.085.05.6724.076.03.17290.018.082.04.5626.074.02.85380.022.078.03.5530.070.02.33470.026.074.02.8533.067.02.03560.030.070.02.3337.063.01.75        (ix) s = \u25b3R2\u25b3R1\\frac{\u25b3R_{2}}{\u25b3R_{1}}\u25b3R1\u200b\u25b3R2\u200b\u200b = R22\u2212R21R12\u2212R11\\frac{R2_{2}-R2_{1}}{R1_{2}-R1_{1}}R12\u200b\u2212R11\u200bR22\u200b\u2212R21\u200b\u200b = 3.1\u221225.25\u22122.75\\frac{3.1-2}{5.25-2.75}5.25\u22122.753.1\u22122\u200b = 1.12.5\\frac{1.1}{2.5}2.51.1\u200b = 0.44    (x) k = &radic;s&nbsp; = &radic;0.44&nbsp; = 0.66    (xi) Precautions:    1. I removed the key from the circuit when readings were not being taken to prevent unnecessary current flow and heating.    2. I ensured all connections were tight and secure to minimize resistance and avoid fluctuations in readings.    3. I avoided error due to parallax when reading the balance point on the metre bridge wire.    4. I confirmed the zero error on the galvanometer and adjusted it if necessary before taking readings.    5. I took multiple readings for each measurement and used consistent experimental conditions for accuracy.    6. I kept the lengths of the resistance wires straight and untangled to ensure accurate measurements.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2024>3>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2024","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : CURRENT ELECTRICITY","question":"State two advantages of potentiometer over voltmeter for measuring potential difference.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Here are some advantages of a potentiometer over a voltmeter for measuring potential difference:  1.\tGreater Accuracy: The potentiometer measures potential difference without drawing current from the circuit, avoiding the loading effect caused by a voltmeter. This ensures more precise measurements.  2.\tNo Power Consumption: Since the potentiometer does not consume current during measurements, it does not affect the circuit's operating conditions, unlike a voltmeter that draws some current.  3.\tWide Range of Measurement: A potentiometer can measure very small to very large potential differences accurately by simply adjusting its settings, while a voltmeter has a limited range.  4.\tDirect Measurement of EMF: A potentiometer can measure the electromotive force (EMF) of a cell directly, whereas a voltmeter measures terminal voltage, which can vary depending on the internal resistance of the cell.  5.\tBetter Resolution: A potentiometer provides higher resolution and sensitivity compared to a voltmeter, making it ideal for detecting small changes in potential difference.  These advantages make the potentiometer particularly useful in laboratory settings and experiments where precise and non-intrusive measurements are critical.Top of Form  Bottom of Form","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2024>3>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2024","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC CURRENT, POTENTIAL DIFFERENCE, RESISTANCE, E.M.F. AND INTERNAL RESISTANCE","question":"Define internal resistance of a cell.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The internal resistance of a cell is the opposition to the flow of electric current within the cell itself, caused by the materials inside the cell, such as the electrolyte and electrodes. It arises due to the resistive nature of these components and the physical and chemical processes occurring in the cell.    Internal resistance affects the cell's performance, as part of the energy supplied by the cell is used to overcome this resistance, reducing the voltage available to an external circuit. It is measured in ohms (\u03a9).","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"}];